\begin_layout Section
Endogenous Growth - Continued
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main conclusions form the endogenous growth model we seen last week
 is that R&D is the main driver of the growth.
 The investment is an endogenous factor, by firms which try to maximize
 profit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scale effect - the larger is the economy, the more R&D is (the marginal
 cost is 0, and there is only the fixed cost of innovation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The crucial element is that technology is non-rival and excludable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number of new innovations each firm produces is a multiple of the innovation
s in the previous period.
 Monopolistic competition might lead to too much / not enough investment.
 There is an externality to technology, as it might generate under-investment
 in R&D.
\end_layout

