\begin_layout Section
Galor-Zeira Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Solow model and the R&D model establish macro growth models with representat
ive agents.
 The next stage is to discuss additional mechanisms that affect growth â€“
 inequality (heterogeneity) being one of them.
 A related topic is poverty traps - which can be discussed using this model
 as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Growth and development are similar but no the same - growth usually refers
 to rich countries, while development usually talks about poorer ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production function is very simple:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=w^{u}L_{t}+w^{s}H_{t}
\]

\end_inset

There are 2 types of workers (skilled and unskilled).
 Unskilled workers become skilled by acquiring education.
 Individuals live in overlapping generaions.
 A generation is born every period and lives for 2 periods, with each individual
 having exactly one parent and one child (e.g someone who makes a decision
 whether to go to college).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first life period individuals get endowments from their parents,
 They invest it either in human capital or physical capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second period they supply labor inelastically, consume and bequeath.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Informally speaking, parents give children money and they use it (in practice,
 parents decide for their offspring).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preferences are defined by the utility function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}^{i}=(1-\beta)logc_{t+1}^{i}+\beta logb_{t+1}^{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
meaning, young individuals do not consume anything (they are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

with the parents
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), therefore they only maximize 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

future utility
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The decision today is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how to invest (and allocate capital) in order to maximize 
\series bold
future
\series default
 utility
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The budget constraint is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{t+1}+b_{t+1}^{i}=I_{t+1}^{i}\Rightarrow b_{t+1}^{i}=b(I_{t+1}^{i})=\beta I_{t+1}^{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This utility models 
\series bold
altruism
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the joy of giving
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) in a very simple way.
 Formally speaking, parents do not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

care
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 about the resulting utility, but only want to give money to their children.
 The essence of this model is capturing the 
\series bold
family ties
\series default
: rich parents give more money to their children, to invest in human capital,
 which increases and get transferred to the next generation, etc...
 - which is a poverty trap when considering a poor family.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a cost 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 invested in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to become skilled in 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gross interest rate for lenders is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and the gross interest rate for borrowers for human capital investment
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>1$
\end_inset

 (market imperfection - the larger is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 - the more there are market imperfections and credit constraints).
\end_layout

