\begin_layout Subsection
Robustness and Endogenous Wages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rancom shocks happen when a fraction of individuals who invested / did not
 invest in human capital become skilled / unskilled workers.
 In most cases having random shocks does not matter, as they don't have
 an important effect - which is not the case here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why is a poor country poor? - Because there are 
\series bold
many 
\series default
poor people.
 A large supply of unskilled workers pushed their salaries down (in rich
 countries the opposit is true - even unskilled workers get a decent salary).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
amplifying effect
\series default
 provides multiple steady states, provided by the 
\series bold
random shocks
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, when the wage of the unskilled workers randomly increase -
 the poverty trap might be escaped.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bottom line: If the economy starts with a low fraction of unskilled/skilled
 workers, it is likely to lead to a steady state in which everyone is skilled/un
skilled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Poverty Traps and the Microfinance Disappointment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the reasons of poverty is the lack of access to credit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thousands of NGOs have been established arouns the worlds to offer the poor
 billions of dollars in affordable interest rates, in order to significantly
 reduce poverty - based on the hope that the problem is only in the credit
 constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Disappointment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There were no significant levels of productive investmens.
 Opportunities tended to be turned down, high return projects were avoided.
 The average business remained small, while the consumption borrowing was
 encouraged (increasing debt).
\end_layout

